\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the following modified form of the dynamical system discussed in
 class:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{x} & = & -x(1-x)(1+x)+\epsilon y,\\
\dot{y} & = & -by+\epsilon x,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{R^{\mathrm{+}}}$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 Assuming that the compact, overflowing invariant manifold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{0}=\left\{ (x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\,:\,x\in\text{\left[-\frac{3}{2},\frac{3}{2}\right],\,\,\,\, y=0 }\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

persists for small 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, determine the expected degree of differentiability of the surviving manifold
 from linearization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-normally hyperbolic by computing the Fenichel-type numbers for all trajectories
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 (Determine the largest possible value of the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for which this statement is true.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The stable and unstable manifolds of a normally hyperbolic invariant manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 turn out to admit a delicate internal structure, an 
\emph on
invariant foliation, 
\emph default
which is useful in determining the exact asymptotic behavior of trajectories
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{u}(M)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{s}(M)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \qquad{}
\end_inset

More specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a compact, 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

 smooth, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional normally hyperbolic, overflowing invariant manifold with boundary,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim\left[W^{s}(M)\right]=k+s$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{s}(M)$
\end_inset

 has the following properties (some of which are sketched in Fig.
 1.):
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fiber.eps
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The geometry of stable fibers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Near 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the stable manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{s}(M)$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{s}(M)=\cup_{p\in M}\,\,f^{s}(p),
\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

 smooth, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-dimensional submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{s}(M)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)\cap M=p$
\end_inset

.
 We refer to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as the base point of the 
\emph on
stable fiber 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) The stable fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

 is tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{p}^{s}M$
\end_inset

, the local section of the stable subbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{s}M.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) The stable fibers form a positively invariant family, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{t}(f^{s}(p))\subset f^{s}(F^{t}(p))$
\end_inset

.
 In words, stable fibers are mapped into stable fibers by the flow map,
 although individual stable fibers are generally not invariant under the
 flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) There exist positive constants 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{s}$
\end_inset

, such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\vert F^{t}(q)-F^{t}(p)\right\vert <C_{s}e^{-\lambda_{s}t}.$
\end_inset

 In other words, trajectories intersecting a stable fiber will exponentially
 converge to the trajectory on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that passes through the base point of that stable fiber.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv) For any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}\in f^{s}(\hat{p}),$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left\Vert F^{t}(q)-F^{t}(p)\right\Vert }{\left\Vert F^{t}(\hat{q})-F^{t}(p)\right\Vert }\rightarrow0,
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, unless 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hat{p}.$
\end_inset

 In other words, out of all the trajectories that may converge to the positive
 half-trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(p)=\left\{ F^{t}(p)\right\} _{t\geq0},
\]

\end_inset

the trajectories starting from the stable fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

 converges at the fastest rate.
 One therefore obtains a local stable manifold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{ss}(\gamma(p))=\cup_{\tilde{p}\in\gamma(p)}\,f^{s}(\tilde{p})
\]

\end_inset

for any trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(p)$
\end_inset

 on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 (The full stable manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{s}(\gamma(p))$
\end_inset

 may be larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{ss}(\gamma(p))$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(p)$
\end_inset

 may also attract trajectories within 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(v) 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)\cap f^{s}(\hat{p})=\emptyset,$
\end_inset

 unless 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hat{p}.$
\end_inset

 In other words, stable fibers with different base points do not intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(vi) A stable fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{s}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r-1}$
\end_inset

 smooth function of its base point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(vii) Stable fibers 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

-smoothly persist under small 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 perturbations of the dynamical system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The local unstable manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{u}(M)$
\end_inset

 has a similar invariant foliation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{u}(M)=\cup_{p\in M}\,\,f^{u}(p),
\]

\end_inset

with appropriate properties in backward time.
 (For more information, see S.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset

 Wiggins, 
\emph on
Normally Hyperbolic Invariant Manifolds in Dynamical
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

Systems
\emph default
, Springer 1994)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the three-dimensional nonlinear dynamical system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{x} & = & -\varepsilon\left(x+y^{2}\right),\\
\dot{y} & = & -y,\\
\dot{z} & = & z,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with the small parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Show that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}=\left\{ y=z=0,\,x\in\left[-1,1\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a normally hyperbolic invariant manifold for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) Find the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 into which 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 perturbs for small 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(c) Using the property (iv), show that for any base point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{s}(M)$
\end_inset

, the corresponding stable fiber is the nonlinear surface.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{s}(p)=\left\{ \left(x,y,z\right)~|~x=x_{p}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2-\varepsilon}y^{2},\,z=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(d) Verify explicitly the properties of the stable fibers listed in (i)-(vii)
 in this example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(e) For any trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

, find explicit expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{ss}(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mathrm{loc}}^{s}(\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
